2. Conduct a multiple regression analysis of verbal memory test scores (vmt) as the dependent variable on a measure of verbal IQ (viq), verbal naming ability (vnt), word fluency ability (wf), duration since injury (dur), and age of injury onset (aoo). 

lm.1 <- lm(vmt ~ viq+vnt+wf+dur+aoo, data=npsych)

3. Produce a formatted summary table of this regression model using tbl_regression from the gtsummary package. 

tbl_initial1 <- tbl_regression(lm.1,
                            intercept = TRUE, 
                            label = list(viq ~ "verbal IQ",
                                         vnt ~ "verbal naming ability",
                                         wf  ~ "word fluency ability",
                                         dur ~ "duration since injury",
                                         aoo ~ "age of injury onset"),
                            pvalue_fun = function(x) style_pvalue(x, digits = 3),
                            estimate_fun = function(x) style_sigfig(x, digits = 2)) %>% 
  add_glance_table(include = c(nobs, adj.r.squared, statistic, df, df.residual, p.value),
                   label = list(nobs ~ "N", 
                                statistic ~ "F-statistic", df ~ "df_reg", df.residual ~ "df_res", 
                                p.value = "p-value")
  )

As a first step in attempting to alleviate collinearity problems, combine all verbal-related predictors into a Verbal Composite Score variable called (verbal) by: + Transforming viq, vnt, and wf into z-scores; + Computing the average of these z-score variables for each participant to create the new (verbal) variable. 

npsych$viq_z <- scale(npsych$viq)
npsych$vnt_z <- scale(npsych$vnt)
npsych$wf_z <- scale(npsych$wf)

npsych$verbal <- rowMeans(npsych[, c("viq_z", "vnt_z", "wf_z")])

4. Describe any differences across these models in terms of the significance of individual predictor variables.

Based on the table, there are differences in terms of the significance of individual predictor variables across the three models.

The predictor variable age is not significant in any of the models, as indicated by the p-values greater than 0.9.

The predictor variable cohes is significant in all three models, with p-values less than 0.001. This suggests that higher levels of group cohesion are associated with lower odds of the outcome, regardless of which other variables are included in the model.

The predictor variable esteem is significant in the first and third models, with p-values of 0.003 and 0.033, respectively. This suggests that higher levels of self-esteem are associated with lower odds of the outcome, after adjusting for other variables.

The predictor variable grades is significant in the first model, with a p-value of 0.017, but is not significant in the second and third models, with p-values of 0.075 and 0.073, respectively. This suggests that the association between grades and the outcome may be confounded by other variables included in the second and third models.

The predictor variable sattach is significant in the first and third models, with p-values of 0.005 and 0.036, respectively. This suggests that higher levels of social attachment are associated with lower odds of the outcome, after adjusting for other variables.

6. Given the large number of 0s in this outcome variable, a zero-inflated regression is probably warranted. Conduct a ZINB regression model with all of the same predictors that were included in the previous exercise. Compute the IRRs and their 95% CIs. Because there are two sets of results (for the count/Poisson and logistic processes), it is not easy to compare these results to the results from a negative binomial or overdispersed model. However, the results of the ZINB model (in the count portion of the model) are largely the same as the NB and overdispersed models in terms of their pattern of significance among the predictors. Given the large number of 0s, the ZINB would be the preferred modeling approach for these data. 

stress.zinb.1 <- zeroinfl(stress ~ age + cohes + esteem + grades + sattach, 
                   data = stress, 
                   dist = "negbin")
